Adapter behavior (per F.5 spec):
  ✓ Adapter object: toolkit='googlecalendar', events=[
      'GOOGLECALENDAR_GOOGLE_CALENDAR_EVENT_CREATED_TRIGGER',
      'GOOGLECALENDAR_GOOGLE_CALENDAR_EVENT_UPDATED_TRIGGER'
    ]. Single adapter handles both Composio slugs.
  ✓ initialState: anchors at new Date().toISOString() — first poll
    only emits events updated AFTER registration, avoids dumping
    the back-catalog of an existing calendar.
  ✓ poll: calls Composio /tools/execute/GOOGLECALENDAR_EVENTS_LIST
    with { calendar_id, updated_min: <last_seen>, single_events: true,
    show_deleted: true, order_by: 'updated', page_token? }. Iterates
    pages (cap 50). Emits one PollAdapterEvent per non-cancelled
    event with payload { event, calendar_id, change_kind }.
  ✓ change_kind detection: per spec literal — `created === updated`
    yields 'created', else 'updated'. Defensible for non-recurring
    instances; for `single_events:true` recurring expansions the
    parent's `created` rarely matches an instance's `updated` so
    those tag as 'updated' (acceptable per spec wording).
  ✓ High-water (last_seen_updated):
      - Bumped on every fetched row (including cancelled/dropped)
        so we never re-fetch stale rows.
      - Persisted alongside last_seen_event_ids: string[] — the IDs
        of events emitted at the exact high-water millisecond.
  ✓ Boundary drop (CRITICAL FIX in review cycle 2):
      - Previous logic dropped EVERY event matching lastSeen ms —
        lost any event sharing that millisecond (bulk import,
        recurring expansion). FIXED to id-aware drop:
        `event.updated === lastSeen && lastSeenIds.has(event.id)`.
      - When the new high-water equals the prior one, merges old
        + new boundary IDs so previously-emitted rows stay
        de-duped indefinitely.
      - New test "a NEW event sharing the boundary millisecond is
        still emitted" exercises exactly this case.
  ✓ Cancelled events: filtered before emit but still advance
    high-water so the sweep doesn't loop on them.
  ✓ Defensive recovery: missing/non-string last_seen_updated →
    silent re-baseline at now(), zero events, no fetch call.
    Mirrors gmail.ts's recovery pattern; protects against corrupted
    composio_poll_state rows.
  ✓ HTTP errors propagate normally so the cron-kicker circuit
    breaker counts them.

